const e='---\ntitle: "APayShop Developer Guide"\ndescription: "Welcome to the APayShop developer documentation"\n---\n\n# APayShop Developer Guide\n\nWelcome to the APayShop developer documentation center. APayShop is a full-stack, geek-style independent store system designed specifically for **virtual products (keys, digital files, service subscriptions, manual top-ups, dynamic APIs)**.\n\nHere, you can learn about the core architecture of the system, the fulfillment mechanisms of various product types, and how to integrate with APayShop via API.\n\n## Core Architecture Features\n\nAPayShop adopts a minimalist yet powerful modern architecture:\n\n- **Ultra-lightweight**: Built on Nuxt 4 + local SQLite (NuxtHub), zero external dependencies, supporting one-click deployment.\n- **Dynamic Template Engine**: The system supports hot-switching of multiple themes without modifying core code to change the frontend UI.\n- **Theme Admin Extensions**: Active themes can now register their own admin extension pages under a unified `/admin/extensions/*` namespace.\n- **Sandbox Payment Callback**: Payment gateways use a plug-in design, parsing logic is stored as pure JS code, and runs safely in a sandbox environment.\n- **Full-scenario Fulfillment Engine**: Supports 5 core product types, covering the vast majority of virtual product trading scenarios.\n\n## Target Audience\n\nThis guide is primarily for:\n\n1. **Secondary Developers**: Engineers who want to perform secondary development, add new features, or write new themes based on APayShop.\n2. **API Integrators**: Users who want to connect to APayShop via API (e.g., calling corresponding interfaces after purchasing Dynamic API products).\n3. **System Administrators**: Webmasters who need to understand the underlying mechanisms of the system (such as product type configuration, order flow) to better operate the website.\n\n## Getting Started\n\nPlease select the module you are interested in from the left navigation bar. If you are new here, it is recommended to read the **Product & Fulfillment Mechanism** chapter first. If you are building custom storefront operations, also review the **Theme Admin Extensions** chapter.\n\n---\n\n## Basic API Conventions\n\nIf you need to call the system\'s open API (such as the purchased `dynamic_api` product), please follow the basic conventions below.\n\n### Base URL\n\nAll API requests should be based on the domain name of your deployed website:\n\n```http\nGET https://yourdomain.com/api\n```\n\n### Response Format\n\nAll API responses are in JSON format. Upon success, it usually contains the requested data:\n\n```json\n{\n  "id": 123,\n  "status": "success",\n  "data": { ... }\n}\n```\n\n### Error Handling\n\nWhen an error occurs, the API will return the corresponding HTTP status code (e.g., 400, 401, 404, 500), accompanied by a JSON response containing error details:\n\n```json\n{\n  "statusCode": 401,\n  "statusMessage": "Unauthorized",\n  "message": "Invalid API key provided."\n}\n```\n';export{e as default};
